[2] Australia (Tasmania): imported
Date: Sat 14 May 2016
Source: ABC [edited]
http://www.abc.net.au/news/2016-05-14/measles-warning-after-infected-traveller-flies-to-launceston/7414752


Tasmanian health authorities warn of a potential measles outbreak, with the state recording its 1st case in 2 years.

The acting director of Public Health, Dr Mark Veitch, said the infected person contracted measles abroad and then travelled from Bangkok to Launceston [north Tasmania], via Melbourne.

"In Australia most measles clusters or even outbreaks start off with a case that comes into the country from overseas. In this case we are sure the person caught their case overseas," he said.

Dr Veitch said anyone exposed to the person could have contracted the illness.

"Measles is one of the most infectious diseases that we know, and it spreads very easily through the air," he said. The symptoms include a fever, cough, sore red eyes, a runny nose and eventually a blotchy rash. Symptoms normally start to appear 10 days after contact with the disease.

The state was last hit with measles in 2014, with 6 confirmed cases.

[Byline: Richard Baines]

