[3] UK (west London)
Date: Mon 16 May 2016
Source: Get West London [edited]
http://www.getwestlondon.co.uk/news/west-london-news/suspected-measles-outbreak-west-london-11325489


West Londoners are being warned of a suspected measles outbreak after cases rocketed in April [2016].

Public Health England (PHE) is calling on people to check their vaccinations are up to date after records revealed a staggering 267 per cent rise from 6 cases in April 2015 to 22 cases reported last month [April 2016]. There were also 23 cases reported in March, up 64 per cent from 14 in the same month in 2015, with most confirmed in teenagers and young adults.

The outbreak of the highly infectious viral illness comes at the same time as reports of high levels of scarlet fever were reported in west London.

Brent saw 7 measles cases in April [2016], compared to just 1 in 2015, while Hounslow saw 6, compared to 1 in 2015, and Hammersmith and Fulham saw 5 compared to 2 in 2015. There were 2 reports of the infection in Harrow, 1 in Ealing and Hillingdon.

No reports of measles were recorded in Westminster or Kensington and Chelsea.

Do you need to be vaccinated?

Dr Yvonne Doyle, regional director for PHE in London, said: "We are seeing an increase in measles cases across London which could be considered an outbreak.

"The cases are being confirmed mainly in adolescents and young adults, and it's never too late for them to have the vaccine.

"Those who have not received 2 doses of the vaccine in the past -- or who are unsure -- should speak to their GP. There's no harm in receiving an additional dose where there is any uncertainty."

In September last year [2015], the number of MMR [measles, mumps, rubella] vaccines dropped across west London.

Signs to spot measles include cold-like symptoms, sore red eyes, high temperature, or a red-brown blotchy rash. PHE advises anyone with these symptoms to seek medical help but to call their GP ahead of visiting to prevent others from being affected.

In addition, pregnant women unsure whether they have been vaccinated with MMR should check with their doctor as rubella can cause serious complications during pregnancy. The vaccination provides mother and baby protection and can be given before becoming pregnant or after birth.

[Byline: Salina Patel]

